The paper discusses the use of electromagnetic induction (EMI) sensors for subsurface explosive hazard detection, which involves signal processing and machine learning techniques. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is the most likely category, as the paper proposes and evaluates new initialization techniques for the Multiple Instance Adaptive Cosine Estimator (MI-ACE), which is a machine learning algorithm. 

cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is also likely, as the paper discusses the use of EMI sensors to discriminate between different types of objects and detect objects with low metal content, which involves image processing and pattern recognition. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another possible category, as the paper proposes and evaluates machine learning techniques for subsurface explosive hazard detection. 

cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is a less likely category, but still possible, as the paper discusses the use of Adaptive Cosine Estimator (ACE) to generate confidence maps, which could be used for information retrieval tasks. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a less likely category, but still possible, as the paper discusses the performance and speed of different initialization techniques for MI-ACE, which involves algorithmic analysis.
